 virginias th district in office march   – january   atlarge march   – january   preceded by r walton moore succeeded by william l scott chairman of the house committee on rules in office january   – january   preceded by leo e allen succeeded by william m colmer personal details born howard worth smith february   broad run virginia died october   aged  alexandria virginia resting place little georgetown cemetery broad run fauquier county political party democratic spouses lillian proctor m – d flu pandemic ann corcoran m  children howard worth smith jr d  violett both by lillian alma mater university of virginia llb profession attorney  howard worth smith february   – october   democratic us representative from virginia was a leader of the powerful but informal conservative coalition which supported both womens rights and racial segregation contents  early life and education  representative  opposition to civil rights  defeat  later life  portrait controversy  portrayals  references  further reading  external links early life and educationedit born in broad run virginia on february   he attended public schools and graduated from bethel military academy warrenton virginia in  he took his llb at the law department of the university of virginia at charlottesville in  was admitted to the bar in  and practiced in alexandria virginia during world war i he was assistant general counsel to the federal alien property custodian from  to  he was commonwealths attorney of alexandria he served as a judge  to  he was often referred to as judge smith even while in congress and also engaged in banking farming and dairying representativeedit he was elected in  to the house of representatives he initially supported new deal measures such as the tennessee valley authority act and the national industrial recovery act a leader of the conservative coalition he led the opposition to the national labor relations board nlrb established by the wagner act of  conservatives created a special house committee to investigate the nlrb that was headed by smith and dominated by opponents of the new deal the committee conducted a sensationalist investigation that undermined public support for the nlrb and more broadly for the new deal in june  amendments proposed by the smith committee passed by a large margin in the house partly because smiths new alliance with william green president of the american federation of labor the afl was convinced the nlrb was controlled by leftists who supported the rival congress of industrial organizations in organizing drives new dealers stopped the smith amendments but roosevelt replaced the ciooriented members on the nlrb with men acceptable to smith and the afl smith proposed the anticommunist alien registration act of   usc §  which became known as the smith act it required resident aliens to register it also banned advocating the overthrow of the us government or its political subdivisions american communist party chairman gus hall was one of many communists later convicted of violating its provisions the us supreme court ruled in yates v united states  that the first amendment protected much radical speech which halted smith act prosecutions under the act opposition to civil rightsedit as chairman of the united states house committee on rules starting in  smith controlled the flow of legislation in the house an opponent of racial integration smith used his power as chairman of the rules committee to keep much civil rights legislation from coming to a vote on the house floor when the civil rights act of  came before smiths committee smith said the southern people have never accepted the colored race as a race of people who had equal intelligence as the white people of the south speaker sam rayburn tried to reduce his power in  with only limited success smith delayed passage the civil rights act of  one of rayburns reforms was the twentyone day rule that required a bill to be sent to the floor within  days under pressure smith released the bill two days before the vote smith offered an amendment to insert sex after the word religion as a protected class of title vii of the act the congressional record shows smith made serious arguments voicing concerns that white women would suffer greater discrimination without a protection for gender liberals who knew smith was hostile to civil rights for blacks assumed that he was doing so to defeat the whole bill but they were unaware of his long connection with white feminists house rules committee clerks record of markup session adding sex to bill in  the burning national issue was civil rights for blacks liberals argued that it was the negros hour and that adding womens rights to the bill could hurt its chance of being passed however conservatives on race voted for the smith amendment the national womans party nwp had used smith to include sex as a protected category and so achieved their main goal the prohibition of sex discrimination was added on the floor by smith while smith was a conservative who strongly opposed civil rights laws for blacks he supported such laws for women smiths amendment passed by a vote of  to  smith expected that republicans who had included equal rights for women in their partys platform since  would probably vote for the amendment some historians speculate that smith in addition to helping women was trying to embarrass northern democrats who opposed civil rights for women since labor unions opposed the clause smith insisted that he sincerely supported the amendment and along with representative martha griffiths was the chief spokeswoman for the amendment for  years smith had sponsored the equal rights amendment with no linkage to racial issues in the house he for decades had been close to the nwp and its leader alice paul one of the leaders in winning the vote for women in  and the chief supporter of equal rights proposals since then she and other feminists had worked with smith since  to try to find a way to include sex as a protected civil rights category griffiths argued that the new law would protect black women but not white women and so was unfair to white women furthermore she argued that the laws protecting women from unpleasant jobs were actually designed to enable men to monopolize those jobs which was unfair to women who were not allowed to try the jobs the amendment passed with the votes of republicans and southern democrats republicans and northern democrats voted for the bills final passage smith had a part in temporarily blocking the economic opportunity act of  because “job corps provision would allow coeducational and interracial job camps” defeatedit after us senator carter glass died in  smith sought the nomination to succeed him the byrd organization of which smith was a member instead nominated a willis robertson who was elected to the senate smith was defeated in the  primary by a considerably more liberal democrat state delegate george rawlings jr after the th district was redistricted to include part of the northern virginia suburbs of washington although smith remained neutral in the general election many of his supporters defected to republican william l scott who soundly defeated rawlings in november later lifeedit smith resumed the practice of law in alexandria where he died at  on october   he was interred in georgetown cemetery broad run virginia portrait controversyedit in january  the house rules committee chairman republican congressman gerald b h solomon had a portrait of smith hung in the committee hearing room the congressional black caucus requested that it be removed georgia congressman john lewis said it is an affront to all of us smith is perhaps best remembered for his obstruction in passing this countrys civil rights laws a man who in his own words never accepted the colored race as a race of people who had equal intelligence and education and social attainments as the white people of the south solomon said he displayed the portrait to acknowledge smiths cooperative work with republicans when he was chairman but that he was unaware of his segregationist views the portrait was later removed portrayalsedit smith was portrayed by american actor ken jenkins in the  hbo tv movie all the way in which his segregationist views posed as a central and divisive opposition to president lyndon b johnsons proposal of the civil rights act of  referencesedit  ticer patsy saslaw richard l ebbin adam moran brian van landingham marian february   senate joint resolution no  on the death of howard worth smith jr virginia general assembly retrieved    a b dierenfield bruce  april  brendan wolfe ed smith howard worth – encyclopedia virginia virginia foundation for the humanities retrieved    storrs p   people in the news runs again the des moines register march    accessdate requires url help  a b c gold michael evan  january  a tale of two amendments the reasons congress added sex to title vii and their implication for the issue of comparable worth faculty publications — collective bargaining labor law and labor history cornell retrieved   from duquesne law review  clinton jacob woods strange bedfellows congressman howard w smith and the inclusion of sex discrimination in the  civil rights act southern studies  spring–summer  –  a b freeman jo march  how sex got into title vii persistent opportunism as a maker of public policy law and inequality a journal of theory and practice   –  online version  harrison cynthia  on account of sex the politics of womens issues  los angeles university of california press pp –   rosenberg rosalind  divided lives american women in the twentieth century pp –   frum david  how we got here the s new york new york basic books pp –  isbn    olson lynne  freedoms daughters the unsung heroines of the civil rights movement p    rosenberg  p notes that smith had been working for years with two virginia feminists on the issue  harrison  p  vinovskis m a  preschool education policies in the kennedy and johnson administrations pp  chicago il university of chicago press  cbc members get portrait removed from house rules committee meeting room  congressional black caucus jet february   retrieved    rosenbaum david e january   offending portrait succumbs to black lawmakers protest new york times retrieved   further readingedit brauer carl m women activists southern conservatives and the prohibition of sex discrimination in title vii of the  civil rights act  journal of southern history february  online via jstor dierenfield bruce j keeper of the rules congressman howard w smith of virginia  dierenfield bruce j conservative outrage the defeat in  of representative howard w smith of virginia virginia magazine of history and biography     freeman jo how sex got into title vii persistent opportunism as a maker of public policy law and inequality a journal of theory and practice vol  no  march  pp – online version gold michael evan a tale of two amendments the reasons congress added sex to title vii and their implication for the issue of comparable worth faculty publications  collective bargaining labor law and labor history cornell   jones charles o joseph g cannon and howard w smith an essay on the limits of leadership in the house of representatives journal of politics    in jstor robinson donald allen two movements in pursuit of equal employment opportunity signs    on alliance between smith and griffiths storrs landon r y civilizing capitalism the national consumers league womens activism and labor standards in the new deal era university of north carolina press  woods clinton jacob “strange bedfellows congressman howard w smith and the inclusion of sex discrimination in the  civil rights act” southern studies  spring–summer  – external linksedit united states congress howard w smith id s biographical directory of the united states congress  howard w smith at find a grave howard w smith at the political graveyard howard smith former us representative  govtrack